  <h1>What is FEMA?</h1>
  <div class="byline"><span class="av">SR</span><b>NumberIQ Glossary</b><span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span></div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>FEMA, the Foreign Exchange Management Act 1999, is the law governing foreign exchange transactions, cross-border investment and remittances in India.</b></p>
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>Administered with the RBI, it governs inbound (FDI) and outbound (ODI) investment, external borrowings and the Liberalised Remittance Scheme, with reporting obligations for each.</p>
  <div class="callout law"><b>Reference.</b> FEMA 1999; RBI regulations.</div>
  <div class="faq"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What does FEMA govern?</summary><p>Foreign-exchange transactions, cross-border investment (FDI/ODI), external borrowings and remittances.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Who administers FEMA?</summary><p>The Reserve Bank of India, through regulations and authorised dealer banks.</p></details>
  </div>
  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2><ul><li>FEMA governs forex and cross-border capital flows.</li><li>Covers FDI, ODI, ECB and LRS.</li><li>Administered with the RBI.</li></ul></div>
